segments.text: Chester Clark by Andrea Hall on November 25th at Gladewater, Texas concerning the Vietnam War.
In the interest of accumulating knowledge about the war, I'm going to donate this tape to the Texas A&M Oral History Collection in the University Archives.
Is that all right with you?
What is your birth date and birthplace?
What is your educational background?
I took the courses at the University of Texas at Tyler, and at Kilgore Junior College and Tyler Junior College.
And what is your bachelor's degree in?
My bachelor's degree was in math and physics.
And what is your master's degree in?
My master's was math and statistics.
I see.
Okay, how and why did you join the military?
When I went to East Texas State at the time, it was East Texas State Teachers College.
And in those days, when you registered, everybody went to the auditorium.
And you got in the line.
You found your letter above a line.
You got in that line and stood in it until you got up to the front of the table.
Then some counselor guided you in what you would take.
And I had a good academic record of high school.
So my counselor advised me to take several one-hour courses so I'd have more hours.
And one of the one-hour courses she said take was ROTC.
And at the time, I wasn't sure what an ROTC was, but I took ROTC.
It was a one-hour course.
And I found that at the beginning of my junior year, they would pay me to stay in ROTC.
And at that time, it was a...
You wore your uniform one time a week, which was kind of neat.
And as I went along in the course, I learned more and more about the military and how it functioned and enjoyed the course.
And at the end of my junior year, we took a physical.
And a lot of people did not pass physical.
I passed it with the qualifications to be a pilot, which again was kind of neat.
So I stayed in ROTC, and at the end of when I graduated, I received a commission in the Air Force.
Had it not been for my counselor, Mrs. O'Neil, I would probably have been in the military.
Wow, what a story.
Could you give me a brief sketch of your military career?
Yes, I went into pilot training, and my basic pilot training was all in Texas at McAllen Air Force Base
in McAllen, Texas, in the far south part of Texas.
Then I went to my basic training at Lubbock, Texas, and went through old airplanes like the T-29 and the B-25.
The B-25 being the bomber that was used in World War II.
We were the last class to go through B-25s.
The next class went into the T-33s, which is jet trainer.
I went to my first flying base was at Savannah, Georgia, Hunter Air Force Base, and I was flying KC-97s.
That's a refueling plane, the one that carries the fuel that we refueled B-52s and B-47s and fighters.
Throughout my military career, I flew the whole time, flying the KC-97 for eight years until I went back to A&M to get my master's, and then
flying C-123s in Vietnam.
And then after Vietnam, I flew a similar airplane at the Pentagon, a T-29.
OK. Now, what is your rank or was your rank?
At the time I was in Vietnam, my rank was captain.
I retired in 1978 as lieutenant colonel.
Right.
And what was the date and place of your tour in Vietnam or any other tours that you served?
Well, I was in the Air Force, the part of the Air Force called Strategic Air Command, and we had limited short tours at a lot of places.
And before going to Vietnam, I had been stationed in Georgia, in Massachusetts, at Otis Air Force Base on Cape Cod.
And during those periods of times, I had short tours in Greenland and Iceland and England and Scotland and other places where we spent like 17 days.
So it wasn't like a long tour like Vietnam.
And right after I got my master's at A&M, I graduated in August of 66 and received my orders to go to Southeast Asia and to survival school.
And other training took me up to February of 67.
I actually arrived in country the 2nd of February, 1967, and spent almost 12 and a half months in Vietnam.
Okay.
And what would you describe your job or service in Vietnam as?
I had actually a split tour.
I was in Saigon at Thompson Air Force Base for six months serving as a wing safety officer.
I did not have the qualifications to be a safety officer, but I was trained on site and served as a safety officer up until the time that my actual boss left country.
And then I could not take his place.
And when the people came in to take his place, they also brought one in to take my place.
So I spent six months at Tan Sanut flying with the 19th Air Commando
squadron and serving as the 315th Air Command Wing safety officer and then I was transferred to Fan Rang where I flew the same airplane but as an aircraft commander.
Alright, now how were you or your unit involved in fighting?
We were, the C-123 was a cargo airplane and we hauled everything in Vietnam.
We hauled vegetables, we hauled ammo, we hauled
People, we hauled families, we hauled families, their belongings, whatever needed to be transported, we transported.
We were unarmed.
There was no weaponry on the airplane itself.
And every time that we were flying to a field, and when I say field, I don't mean two miles of concrete.
I mean a field.
The C-123 was assigned to land on dirt.
And we landed at a lot of dirt strips.
And the 123 was an airplane designed to land right at stall speed, which means that you'd make a very, very steep approach into the place that you were landing at a very, very low rate of speed.
So when you hit the ground, you kill the throttles and stopped almost immediately.
Well, flying at a very, very low rate of speed meant that you were very subject to being shot at.
And we took a lot of hits that were towards the back of the airplane.

that that was the if you talk about combat for shooting that was the combat now we did fly in a lot of areas where you know shells were being lobbed in and shots were going out we were in that kind of combat but we were not the we were not the fighters if you will we were involved in what other people were doing around us all right now we already talked a little bit about your training before you went to vietnam do you feel like you were adequately trained to go to vietnam
For the job I did, yes.
Now, I wasn't trained to be a safety officer, but I didn't know I was going to be a safety officer until I got there, and they didn't know I was either, so that doesn't count.
But for the flying I was doing, my training was in Florida at Herbert Field, and I trained with Vietnamese as well as with instructors who had been to Vietnam.
The problems that we had were not problems that you would even think about.
The airplane itself had flying characteristics that didn't lend itself to a short person.
The Vietnamese were short people.
So we were trained to fly with, to handle those kinds of characteristics that people might have.
For instance, we were not only carrying cargo, we were also a drop plane where people bailed out of the plane.
And in several of the drops that we made, the Vietnamese were not heavy enough to make their parachutes go where they wanted them to.
So we had to learn that if you were dropping Vietnamese, you had to drop them at a different point than you would drop in America.
Because they would float so far.
And later on, I will tell you about dropping some Vietnamese into the bay at Cam Ranh Bay.
We actually dropped them in the water.
And they continued to drift beyond where we planned to drop them.
All right.
How did you perceive military leadership in Vietnam?

When you think about leadership, and you can think about the president or the commanders or whatever, but the leadership that I was most familiar with that I can really address is my immediate leadership.
I was not really affected by the decisions being made by the army commanders.
My job was based on flying supplies where they were needed in Vietnam.
And that need was, it was like, you know when you get up in the morning, there's certain things you do to get ready to go outside.
Well, our job in Vietnam for flying supplies was well known.
You just, you're only, all I had to know was, where are they and where do they go?
So my orders were, could have been given by anyone because the need was there and we saw it.
And we flew anything from bob wire, which was served as a constant wire around the camp, to stakes to hold it down,
to vegetables for the food for the people, because that's a tough thing to get in country.
We had other missions that involved doing things like even flying bodies back to Saigon where the mortuary was.
So it was a very, you did what needed to be done.
It encompassed many things.
Without someone having to say, today you will.
Okay.
During your tour, did you encounter any drugs within your unit or among fellow servicemen?
No drugs like you mean drugs.
But the drug that we encountered the most was alcohol.
And the problem that I personally had, I was a captain.
I had been in the Air Force 12 years at the time.
I had a good flying record.
And from the write-ups that I had, that I can look back now, and from remembering what I did, I was very proud of my ability to fly the airplane.
A lot of people, and as I got older and still flew, I realized how my limitations were creeping up on me, how my reflexes were not as fast.
I could not do things as quickly.
And some of the people that we had in Vietnam were sent straight from a desk to Vietnam to fly.
These were lieutenant colonels that had served in combat, had good records, but suddenly were thrown into another combat situation that they didn't want to be in.
that they, it's not that they didn't want to be in Vietnam, they didn't want to be in a combat situation.
They did not object to going to Vietnam.
But once they were there, they knew they couldn't perform like they could in the past, or like we were, like the younger people were performing.
And they turned to alcohol.
And quite often, someone, in order to get there, to be ready to fly, they would have to drink the night before to be ready to fly the next morning.
And that didn't,
That bothered me because there were people who were not drinkers before they arrived in Vietnam who were alcoholics when they left.
During your tour, did you encounter many people who were trying to capitalize on the war?
The Americans that would, quote, capitalize on the war were...
were ones who were taking advantage of something that they gave each of us to.
And I did it myself.
We could invest money in a savings account at, at the time, a 10% interest.
Now, at the time, that was a good interest rate.
It's nothing now, but it was then.
And we had people that you could put in $10,000 into a savings account at 10% interest.
But that was limited to $10,000.
If you extended your tour of duty, you could invest another $10,000.
So the people who were taking advantage of that, if you will, were single airmen or single enlisted that would continue their tour.
I know that's not your question, but that is a way that people were, quote, taking advantage of the war.
As for prolonging it for any personal gain,
I didn't see anyone doing that, either Americans, Vietnamese.
There was black market.
There were things that happened that some supplies and things that we couldn't get, you could buy on the black market, which kind of makes you feel like we're here.
We're here, quote, fighting for these people.
Why don't they just give it back and let us have it?
And an item such as sunglasses, you couldn't get it through the regular PX or through the base supply, but you could out on the black market at downtown Saigon and buy a pair.
three or four or five times as much for them as they would from the PX.
But electronic gear.

Now, in the middle of a conflict, in the middle of a war, in the middle of a place where people were dying, it seemed stupid to think that a tape recorder or a tape deck or speakers would be a big item.
But they were.
These things were black market items.
And some of the stories that were told that when the PX equipment would arrive at the base, most of it would be siphoned off and go downtown before it ever reached the base.
I didn't see that happen.
I was not in a position to see that happen.
I did see American goods and military gear downtown for sale.
I don't know how it got there, but it got there.
Someone did profit from this, as we know from some of the people later on, some of the supply sergeants who later on were caught and prosecuted for dealing in the black market.
Do you think Vietnam escalated careerism among officers?
Not per se.
It did help you in your career.

And for me, the first thing that helped me in my career, as a lieutenant going through pilot training, the first rank that you would make after first lieutenant would be captain, and normally captain was in seven years.
I made captain in five and a half years because they changed the rules.
That was a career move for me, per se.
An Army major was made in about 17 years.
I made a major in less than 12 years because that was how they changed it.
Now, I became a regular officer because at the time they were promoting to regular officer.
It wasn't a promotion.
Being a reserve officer, regular officer meant different things to you.
Mine meant that I could retire 20 years with full benefits, if you will.
When I made captain and then made regular officer, the criteria that was looked at was your educational background.
I had the educational background that they were looking for at the time.
It didn't matter that it was in math and physics.
It mattered that I had it because people with the music background, with veterinarian backgrounds, with whatever background, made it because of the education.
When I made major, they were looking at an educational level, which was a master's, and they were looking at Vietnam experience.
I had both, so I made major.
It's not that I went to Vietnam to help my career, but by being in Vietnam, it helped.
And then I had a Pentagon tour, which helped me to make Lieutenant Colonel.
So the promotions were, I didn't do those things to make the promotions, but the promotions were helped by them.
And Vietnam helped.
did help commanders make decisions.
Who would receive different ranks.
When you were in Vietnam, did you know who the enemy were?
I did, and it was very difficult sometimes to accept the fact that as a Vietnamese living in Vietnam, some of the farmers, merchants, ranchers, wherever were there, they really didn't care who
was in control of them.
They just knew that if the Americans were, then they kept all their money that they made.
They kept all their crops.
They knew if the North Vietnamese were, then they gave up their money.
They gave up their crops.
But they kept their life.
They lived either way.
They'd get along with you if you invade today.
They'd get along with me if I'd run you out today.
Sometimes the farmers would...
would take sides, if you will.
And when one particular mission we were flying, we flew over a pretty green valley in a little stream.
And it was a farmer out plowing his field.
And we stayed low on purpose, which you normally didn't do.
And we stayed low on purpose.
As we flew over, the farmer, he waved, we waved, and then we made a circle and came back.

And he dropped his plow and ran over to the tree and picked up a gun and shot at us as we made our next pass by, which the weapon he was using was like a .22, and the shell that came out of it was like a .22, but it wasn't a .22.
It wasn't very accurate or precise.
In fact, it was something that they looked like they had made themselves, like a ball that would be made for an old gun.
But to us, it was kind of, I don't know how you take someone shooting at you, but we just cracked up laughing because here's this farmer.
And we flew over one time, and I don't know if we disturbed him and flew the next time.
But we were the enemy to him at that time.
He was just outside of Benoit Air Force Base and was being protected by the military there.
But we became the enemy to him then as we flew over.
But as for being in an actual firefight and having to look at this one and say, oh, your eyes sloped this way, therefore you're a bad Vietnamese, or this way you're a good Vietnamese.
If you had to pick out the enemy...
from a lineup, you'd never pick it out.
I don't mean to say that all Chinamen are laundry people, but the Vietnamese did look the same.
They could be a communist today and non-communist tomorrow, depending on who was in power.
Could you tell me about the time you stayed in the hotel that was run by the Viet Cong?
My first place I stayed in Saigon was in a hotel.
And it was all military in the hotel.
And my first week in country, I bought a camera like everybody buys a camera.
And we, was being martyred one night.
And when the base is being mortared, they put up flares.
And they have Puff the Magic Dragon was a C-47.
It had a machine gun mounted inside of it.
And they would put up flares that would illuminate the area.
And the C-47s would fire.
Every third bullet would be a tracer that you could see.
So the mortars were coming in this way.
The flares were being put up.
And the C-47s would fly in a tight circle and shoot in an area.
It would look like a Christmas tree, the way the tracer shells were showing up in every third one.
I was on top of my building taking pictures.
of this, and the kid that was with me, my roommate, was Joe Driscoll.
And Joe and I got very tickled at this.
Here we are in the middle of a combat zone, taking pictures of the base that we're stationed at being mortared by, quote, the enemy.
And we're up there taking pictures of it and thinking how pretty it is.
Well, the hotel we were in was right next to an army barracks.
And in one of the times just before I left Saigon,
There was a hit on Saigon itself.
There was a hit on the embassy, on the army barracks, and on several places around us.
But our hotel never was hit.
And our motorcycles stayed down on the porch and were never stolen, never touched.
And we found out later on that our landlord got on the motel, paid off the Viet Cong, and was indeed part, you know, he had allegiance to whoever was
in power at the time.
And he paid off the Viet Cong.
His hotel was never hit our whole time there.
It's very interesting.
What honors have you, what military honors have you received?
In Vietnam, I received the Vietnamese Service Medal and the Vietnamese Combat Medal.
I received air medals for my flying.
And for one particular mission that we flew on Easter Sunday, I received a distinguished flying cross.
All right, can you explain to me what each of these honors means?
The Vietnamese combat and Vietnamese service medals are like our national service defense medal.
If you served in the military in the country, you received those medals.
The air medal was reserved for pilots, Air Force pilots who flew a certain number of missions or certain types of missions in country.
And the missions
that just before I arrived in Vietnam, for each mission that a pilot flew, each time he took off and landed counted as a mission.
And for 35 missions, a pilot would receive an air medal.
They changed this to be 35 days of flying, a mission being from that morning till that night, rather than 35 missions.
Because in some of the missions that we would fly,
you would fly like a 20-minute hop from one place to another, and you'd fly that all day long.
And on one particular day, you might fly 35 or 40 of those hops back and forth, back and forth, which would have meant an air medal.
So some people were leaving country as I arrived with 10 and 12 and 14 and 15 air medals.
When I changed it to 35 days, that meant that in a year's time, you were going to get
and maybe four or five air medals.
So an air medal was for flying a particular kind of mission.
The Distinguished Flying Cross was for a mission above and beyond the call of duty.
And our particular mission was a very, it started off as just like any other mission.
It was a normal type mission, but escalated into a lot different than what we thought.
We were flying at a place called Zomcat,
And it was fairly safe in the morning.
We were flying in the morning.
We had helicopter gunships for protection.
But as the day wore on, we were evacuating the Vietnamese, the Americans, and the mountain yards out of this particular village.
And it was a village associated with a base.
It was about to be overrun by the VC.
The gunships were holding the VC at bay while we took the people out.
We kept loading the airplane up to its maximum and taking them out.
The gunships were overextended and ran out of fuel and had to return home.

replacement gunships were diverted somewhere else for a more serious mission so we were flying in unarmed to haul these people out and on the last three missions we were actually surrounded by the vc and we're taking hits as we're taking them out they're being held off by gunfire from within the perimeter as we were hauling them out and we put the last people on board and when you fly an airplane
there's a limit to the amount of weight you put on the airplane.
It's called the design gross weight.
When you exceed the design gross weight, then the airplane becomes rock and doesn't fly.
Well, the last mission we knew we had very little time, and we could not make any more runs in.
Because the last four, as we were coming in, you could watch the perimeter of the base being closed in on.
And we could see how far out the people were.
And they were right up on the, within a couple hundred yards of the base on our last mission.
So we put everybody on the airplane.
Everybody.
And it was kind of interesting.
In the middle of all this, the Americans, it was almost like integration.
The Americans got on the front part of the airplane.
The Vietnamese were in the middle part.
Then the Cambodians in the mountain yards were in the back.
They sat in the back of the bus.
And the cargo compartment of C-123 closes with a ramp that comes up from the ground, and then a ramp that comes down from inside the airplane, and they meet.
But we had people on the ramp that goes out of the plane, and we brought it up.
They were actually at an angle in the back of the plane where that loaded.
And we took off.
The dirt strip we were taking off from was not really long enough to take off from.
And as we took off, we
barely cleared the treetops to get out.
And as we took off and circled back, the VC actually infiltrated where we were and they had set explosives to blow up the communications equipment and the artillery they had to leave behind.
They actually infiltrated as we were

pulling out and the things were it was I took there I was typically American I was taking pictures because this was blowing up and it was it was it was it was interesting the last probably all afternoon all the missions we flew in were based on this in fact one time one time they ran out of ammunition
So we changed, we diverted from going straight back and picked up ammo and took it in so they'd have the ammo to withstand the onslaught in the afternoon.
What other operations were you involved in that were successes?
Well, there were some that were more important than others, but probably not more important in the end result.
One of the missions that I remember that was a super success was on Christmas Day.
We had been flying, I flew with the Special Forces most of my, the time I was in country.
I started with them because in Saigon as a safety officer, I would fly on the weekends.
And there we had weekends as well as weekdays.
I would fly on the weekends to give other people weekends off.
And when I started flying with these people, they were a special brand of folks, special forces.
And one thing that they were talking about was that they really wanted for Christmas, they wanted some beer and Playboy magazines.
So on Christmas Day, one of the missions that we flew was to fly over and drop to them beer and Playboy magazines.
Super successful mission.
The other missions, some of them, one of the most satisfying missions I had was one when I really, I was flying out of
That's terrible.
I can't remember the name of the base we were flying out of.

Anyway, we were flying out of one of the northern bases that was a big supply base, and we were flying into the various sundry special forces areas, and we flew into one with the cargo that we were told to take to them.
And the cargo we took to them was steel spikes to hold down the concertina wire.
And we landed, and we offloaded, and we were expecting them to come out and say, great, we really need this.
And the first thing we heard was, why the hell did you bring this?
We have, look.
And you look over there, and there's just mounds of steel spikes.
And I said, well, the frag order says steel spikes.
Bring it in.
They said, we don't want the steel spikes.
Bring us ammo.
We were hit last night.
Half the ammo was wet.
It didn't fire.
We need ammo.
So I went back to the supply point, and I told the people there, I said, I don't want to take those.
I want to take ammo.
And they said, you can't.
This is what it says you take, and it's what you take.
I said, no, that's not how it works.
The commander needs ammo.
He needs it now.
He doesn't need to charge.
Well, you have to talk to the major in charge.
I remember I was the captain at the time.
So I talked to the major in charge, and he says, Captain, you'll take what we tell you to take.
I said, no, sir.
We won't.
And at the time, since I had been on the wing staff in Saigon, I knew the commander, and he knew me.
And I called him, and I said, General Brown, I'm not having a problem.
And I told him what the problem was.
And he said, let me talk to the major.
And of course, the major was very upset that the captain said, I'll take this cargo and not this.
It was very satisfying to fly into that base with ammo.
and offload ammo and see these guys say, we couldn't have stayed last another night without it.
We appreciate your bringing what we need.
